	<h2>The Repair vs. Replace Decision Framework</h2>

	<h3>Quick Decision Criteria</h3>
	<p>Use this checklist for immediate guidance:</p>

	<p><strong>Strongly Consider Replacement When:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li>Fence is beyond 75% of expected lifespan for its material</li>
		<li>More than 30% of fence sections show damage or deterioration</li>
		<li>Structural posts are failing or leaning (4+ posts)</li>
		<li>Repair costs exceed 50% of replacement cost</li>
		<li>Multiple repair types needed simultaneously</li>
		<li>Previous repairs have failed within 2 years</li>
		<li>Fence no longer serves primary purpose (privacy, security, appearance)</li>
		<li>Upgrading for home sale or major landscape renovation</li>
	</ul>

	<p><strong>Repair Is Usually Best When:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li>Fence is less than 50% through expected lifespan</li>
		<li>Damage isolated to one section or area</li>
		<li>Only cosmetic issues or minor structural problems</li>
		<li>Repair costs under 30% of replacement cost</li>
		<li>Overall fence structure remains sound</li>
		<li>Replacement not planned for 3+ years</li>
		<li>Budget constraints make replacement unfeasible now</li>
	</ul>

